-- European shares fall; Rio surges on M&A news
-- By Blaise Robinson
-- Tue Oct 07, 2014 03:16AM EDT
-- None



PARIS, Oct 7 (Reuters) - European shares slipped in early trading on Tuesday as data showing Germany's industrial output falling far more than expected spooked investors, although losses were limited by a rally in mining shares boosted by M&A news.

Shares in Rio Tinto <RIO.L> surged 5.3 percent, while Anglo American <AAL.L> added 2.9 percent and BHP Billiton <BLT.L> gained 1.2 percent. Rio said it rejected a merger approach from smaller rival Glencore <GLEN.L> to create a $160 billion mining and trading giant. [ID:nL3N0S14B2] At 0712 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 <.FTEU3> index of top European shares was down 0.6 percent at 1,341.77 points. Germany's DAX <.GDAXI> was down 0.8 percent. Germany posted its biggest drop in industrial production since the financial crisis in early 2009, Economy Ministry data showed on Tuesday, the latest figures to raise question marks about Europe's largest economy. [ID:nL6N0S20ET]